Signed-off-by: Michael Heimpold <mhei@heimpold.de>

Always open value file using O_RDWR flag.

Changing file access mode on fd does not work in Linux. See "man fcntl":
F_SETFL (int)
  Set the file status flags to the value specified by arg.  File  access
  mode  (O_RDONLY,  O_WRONLY,  O_RDWR)  and  file  creation flags (i.e.,
  O_CREAT, O_EXCL, O_NOCTTY, O_TRUNC) in arg are ignored.  On Linux this
  command  can  change  only the O_APPEND, O_ASYNC, O_DIRECT, O_NOATIME,
  and O_NONBLOCK flags.

ugpio_full_open: do not fail when direction and/or edge is not exported via sysfs

On some boards that don't export edge and/or direction file for pins in sysfs,
there is a bug in ugpio.c that makes ugpio_full_open fail in this case.
This patch should correct these issues.

Bump version to 0.0.4

Signed-off-by: Michael Heimpold <mhei@heimpold.de>

Clamp return values of *_get_value to boolean range

There exists some kernel versions where platforms (e.g. mxs) pass
the internal value of gpio_get_value via sysfs.
A fix is on the way, see https://lkml.org/lkml/2014/3/11/58 for
reference, however, we can catch this here, too.

Signed-off-by: Michael Heimpold <mhei@heimpold.de>

Fix a problem with gpio_request_one

Say that the gpio pin has already been exported when gpio_request_one is
called. If any of the calls to gpio_direction_input, gpio_alterable_edge,
gpio_set_edge, etc fail. Then gpio_request_one will erroneously
unexport the pin before returning.
